==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Copaiva
<hw>Co*pai"va</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. & Pg., fr. Brazil.
<ets>cupa⟦uacute⟧ba</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A more or less
viscid, yellowish liquid, the bitter oleoresin of several species of
<gen>Copaifera</gen>, a genus of trees growing in South America and the
West Indies. It is stimulant and diuretic, and was formerly much used in
affections of the mucous membranes. It is also used in varnishes and
lacquers, and in cleaning oil paintings. -- called also <altname>balsam
of copaiba</altname>, <altname>copaiba balsam</altname>, <altname>balsam
capivi</altname>, and <altname>Jesuits' resin</altname>.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>capivi</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

